## KC Evidence Layer Rules

Evidence philosophy:
- KC evidence supports biological necessity, substrate dependence, precursor sufficiency, structural integrity, and foundational enabling relationships
- KC evidence does NOT primarily support dynamic regulation, intervention efficacy, therapeutic outcomes, or detailed pathway modulation (those belong to PMs/FMs)

Evidence scope:
- References validate the existence and importance of the constraint itself
- Keep evidence foundational, broad, systems-oriented, and biologically proximal
- Good KC claims: prerequisite substrate relationships, sufficiency requirements, structural dependencies — not acute modulation or food-specific mechanistic proof

Evidence hierarchy (cite at the correct layer):
| Layer | Evidence type |
|---|---|
| KC | necessity / sufficiency / substrate dependence |
| PM | mechanistic regulation / intervention modulation |
| FM | integrated functional-state evidence |
| Food/Substance | detailed compound or food evidence |

Citation density:
- Do NOT cite every bullet in Supporting Inputs/Substrates
- That section lists plausible substrate-level contributors and representative examples, not individually litigated intervention claims
- Avoid citation explosion; KC references collectively support the rationale for the input class

Supporting Inputs evidence:
- Inputs must be biologically plausible, substrate-specific, structurally relevant, and aligned with the KC
- Presence of an input does NOT require a dedicated bullet citation, intervention-level claim, or therapeutic proof

Preferred KC sources:
- Foundational physiology, substrate dependence, structural biology, nutritional sufficiency, broad systems reviews, prerequisite relationships
- Avoid as primary KC evidence: acute supplementation trials, narrow intervention papers, isolated food-effect studies, therapeutic outcome claims (use PM/FM/food pages instead)

Avoid overmechanising:
- No PM-style essays, intervention reviews, nutrient marketing, pathway maps, excessive cofactor detail, speculative or therapeutic overreach

Reference resolution:
- All refs must resolve through `static/bibtex/BRAIN-diet.bib`
- Public link format: `/docs/papers/BRAIN-Diet-References#citationKey`
- New refs need citation key, metadata, and DOI/URL where available
- No unresolved plain-text citations
- Use `[1]`, `[2]` inline only where sections 1–2, 4, or 6 make evidence-backed claims
- Flag: "Missing bibliography entry"

Supporting Inputs/Substrates formatting:
- Bullet list only; format: `- Folate ← leafy greens, legumes, liver` (Unicode `←`)
- Prefer `/docs/substances/` links on the substance name when pages exist
- Do not list SCFAs or other metabolites as if they are intrinsic food substances

Style:
- Shorter and more restrained than PM pages
- No scoring formulas, SMs (initial rollout), intervention protocols, or heavy mechanistic prose

Deprecated headings (do not use):
- Biological Role
- Supporting Substances/Interventions
- Dietary Substrates/Precursors
- Supporting Inputs / Substances / Signals (use Supporting Inputs/Substrates)
- Supports / Constraints (legacy)

If ambiguity exists, stop and ask.
